{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client payload handoff. A unit test of a helper can miss wiring bugs where the API adapter omits labels. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text focusing on request construction (\"request sent ... includes ... labels\"), not real OS/network effects or model judgment quality.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub API client that records outbound payload; invoke classify and assert the transmitted prompt/fields contain every taxonomy label exactly once per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local normalization/validation logic on returned label values. The real failure is in mapping logic, not infrastructure interaction. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text specifying deterministic fallback behavior (\"returns 'unknown'\") from a given returned label.","test_description":"Call normalization/response-handling function with a fixed taxonomy and an out-of-taxonomy label; assert output is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets determinism of normalization for identical inputs, which is pure local logic. Integration/System/Agentic are disqualified by text limiting scope to \"normalization step\" with identical raw response fixtures.","test_description":"Invoke normalization twice (or many times) with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI calls and consistency tied to provider behavior. A stub cannot expose model/provider nondeterminism. Workflow is disqualified because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N live classifications for same document/taxonomy against real provider; log raw provider outputs and final labels; assert final label only changes when raw provider response meaningfully changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at handoff between budget enforcement and dispatch path (e.g., over-budget requests still sent). In-process wiring with fake client is sufficient; no real OS/network required. Higher levels are disqualified by text focusing on pre-dispatch policy enforcement, not model output quality.","test_description":"Configure low token budget, use inputs above and below threshold, and a fake dispatch client; assert module truncates/rejects per policy and only dispatches compliant payloads.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This depends on real AI provider token accounting on real calls; mocks can hide true provider tokenizer/usage behavior. Integration is disqualified because correctness depends on actual AI API response fields (usage), not only local orchestration. Workflow is disqualified because only one model call is evaluated per check.","test_description":"Execute live classification for representative documents and compare provider-reported usage fields against configured budget; fail if any call exceeds budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across module and API client interface. A controllable fake client returning rate-limit then success catches real logic failures (wait/retry/propagation). System is disqualified because real network is not required to reproduce this behavior; Agentic is disqualified because assertions do not depend on model output quality.","test_description":"Use stub client sequence: rate-limit error then success; assert module performs backoff/wait and retries, eventually returning success instead of surfacing immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.66,"System":0.24,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}}]}
